<h2 id="adp">ADP Run -- For Growing Past 50 Employees</h2>

ADP is the enterprise payroll standard. ADP Run is their small business product -- capable, comprehensive, and more complex than most small operators need.

<h3>When ADP makes sense:</h3>

<ul>
  <li>You have 50+ employees and need enterprise-grade compliance</li>
  <li>You operate in many states with complex tax situations</li>
  <li>You need dedicated payroll support with a named account manager</li>
  <li>Your benefits administration is complex (multiple plan types, multi-tier)</li>
</ul>

<h3>When ADP doesn't make sense:</h3>

<ul>
  <li>You have under 50 employees (Gusto does everything you need at lower cost)</li>
  <li>You want transparent pricing (ADP requires a quote)</li>
  <li>You want self-service simplicity (ADP's platform has enterprise complexity)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Quote-based. Typical small business pricing starts around $59/mo + $4/employee, but varies significantly based on services selected.</p>

ADP is the platform you graduate to when Gusto's scale limits become a factor. For most multi-location operators under 100 employees, that day hasn't arrived yet.

<h2 id="paychex">Paychex Flex -- The Enterprise Middle Ground</h2>

Paychex sits between Gusto and ADP in complexity and capability. It's a full-service payroll provider with HR, benefits, time tracking, and compliance tools -- more features than Gusto, less complexity than ADP.

<h3>Paychex strengths:</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Dedicated payroll specialist</strong> -- a named person handles your account</li>
  <li><strong>Comprehensive HR</strong> -- hiring, onboarding, performance management, employee handbook builder</li>
  <li><strong>Strong compliance</strong> -- proactive notifications about regulatory changes</li>
  <li><strong>Industry-specific solutions</strong> -- restaurant, healthcare, construction-specific payroll features</li>
</ul>

<h3>Paychex weaknesses:</h3>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Pricing is opaque</strong> -- requires a quote, makes comparison difficult</li>
  <li><strong>Contract terms</strong> -- some plans require multi-year commitments</li>
  <li><strong>Interface is dated</strong> -- functional but not modern</li>
  <li><strong>Overkill for most</strong> -- the feature depth is wasted if you need basic payroll</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Quote-based. Typically $39-69/mo + $5-9/employee depending on plan and services. Multi-year contracts may offer discounts but reduce flexibility.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Operators with 50-200 employees who want more hand-holding than Gusto provides but aren't ready for full ADP enterprise. The dedicated specialist model works well for operators who don't have an internal HR person.</p>

